==English==

===Proper noun===
'''Abraham'''

# A male [[given name]] of biblical origin, meaning "father/leader of many".
# A prophet in the [[Old Testament]].
# [[Semitic]] [[archfather]]. Father of the [[Jewish]] archfather [[Isaac]] (by his wife [[Sarah]]) and the [[Arabic]] archfather [[Ishmael]] (by his concubine [[Hagar]]).

===Etymology===
From the Greek [[Αβραάμ]] (Avraám), through Late Latin; from the Hebrew [[אברהם|אַבְרָהָם]] ('Abrāhām). Possibly compounded from [[אב|אָב]] (av) 'father' + [[המון]] (hamon) 'multitude' (father of a multitude of nations). Abram, Hebrew [[אברם|אַבְרָָם]], 'high father', [[אב|אָב]] (av) 'father' + [[רם|ְַרָָם]] (ram) 'high'.

